    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-01-09T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-01-09T00:00:00-05:00" n="569"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d569">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 <gloss target="#t_PW1">PW</gloss>
                    1939/1–945</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul at Colombo</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_BMW1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bishop</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the Secretary of State</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="#p_SERJ1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Stettinius</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                        <lb/> No. 22</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Colombo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-01-09">January 9,
                            1945</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: … I have the honor to report that the British
                    Political Adviser<note n="1" xml:id="d569fn1">
                        <persName corresp="#p_DME1">Maberly Esler Dening</persName>.</note> to the
                    Supreme Allied Commander<note n="2" xml:id="d569fn2">Admiral <persName
                            corresp="#p_MLL1">Mountbatten</persName>.</note> has recently stated
                    that <gloss target="#t_SEAC1">SEAC</gloss> considers French Indochina to be
                    “open territory” in which <gloss target="#t_SEAC1">SEAC</gloss> may operate at
                    any time that it is militarily feasible.</p>
                <p>This official pointed out that at the Cairo meeting Admiral <persName
                        corresp="#p_MLL1">Mountbatten</persName> discussed the question of Thailand
                    and French Indochina as military theatres with <gloss target="#t_Generalissimo1"
                        >Generalissimo</gloss>
                    <persName corresp="#p_CKS1">Chiang Kai-shek</persName>
                    <note n="3" xml:id="d569fn3">See <hi rend="italic">ante</hi>, <ref
                            target="#pg_391">p. 391</ref>.</note> and asked the <gloss
                        target="#t_Generalissimo1">Generalissimo</gloss> to agree to the inclusion
                    of French Indochina in the <gloss target="#t_SEAC1">SEAC</gloss> theatre. The
                        <gloss target="#t_Generalissimo1">Generalissimo</gloss> refused to give his
                    agreement, and Admiral <persName corresp="#p_MLL1">Mountbatten</persName> then
                    suggested that, although the U. S. Joint Chiefs of Staff had approved the
                    inclusion of Thailand in <gloss target="#t_SEAC1">SEAC</gloss>, Admiral
                        <persName corresp="#p_MLL1">Mountbatten</persName> was willing not to
                    publish this fact provided the <gloss target="#t_Generalissimo1"
                        >Generalissimo</gloss> agreed to <gloss target="#t_SEAC1">SEAC</gloss>
                    operations in Indochina if they became militarily feasible. In other words, it
                    was suggested that the two Supreme Allied Commanders agree orally that forces
                        <pb facs="0991" n="887" xml:id="pg_887"/> under either one might operate in
                    either French Indochina or Thailand and that those areas would become a part of
                    the theatre of the commander whose forces reached there first. The <gloss
                        target="#t_Generalissimo1">Generalissimo</gloss> is said to have accepted
                    this arrangement. …</p>
                <p rend="center">. . . . . . . . . . . . . .</p>
                <p>Respectfully yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_BMW1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Max</hi> W. <hi rend="smallcaps">Bishop</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
